2022-01-20 21:45:08	<--	skapata (~Skapata@user/skapata) has quit (Ping timeout: 250 seconds)
2022-01-20 21:46:24	causative_	if you want to understand consciousness, one important tool is to ask what would happen to consciousness if parts of your brain were altered smoothly and continuously
2022-01-20 21:46:54	causative_	to understand what happens in these hypothetical scenarios, we need to look at how they effect behavior, such as whether you *say* your consciousness is changing
2022-01-20 21:47:01	causative_	*affect
2022-01-20 21:47:17	-->	skapata [skapata] (Skapata Lambda 1337) (~Skapata@user/skapata) has joined ##philosophy
2022-01-20 21:47:34	causative_	for example, "what if all your neurons were gradually replaced with functionally identical nanites?" is one such scenario
2022-01-20 21:47:38	ProfSimm	causative_: we can mess with consciousness, but it still doesn't quite explain its existence
2022-01-20 21:47:44	causative_	and the answer is, you wouldn't notice anything
2022-01-20 21:47:56	ProfSimm	causative_: my hot take is that moving information is conscious
2022-01-20 21:47:58	causative_	because the premise that they are functionally identical to the neurons means that your behavior wouldn't change
2022-01-20 21:48:31	causative_	and "noticing anything different" would be a change in behavior
2022-01-20 21:49:23	ProfSimm	inhahe_: wasn't it one of your essays that said that consciousness is moving information?
2022-01-20 21:49:26	causative_	you also wouldn't be trapped inside your brain watching yourself do things you can't control - because the process happens gradually, and such an experience would certainly provoke an emotional reaction, which would be a big change in your neural patterns, which by hypothesis aren't changing
2022-01-20 21:49:35	ProfSimm	inhahe_: patterns in motion rather, I guess
2022-01-20 21:50:26	ProfSimm	causative_: I already watch myself do things I can't control
2022-01-20 21:50:28	ProfSimm	;-)
2022-01-20 21:50:47	causative_	not relevant
2022-01-20 21:51:06	ProfSimm	 causative_ so this experiment, how would it go you think
2022-01-20 21:51:22	ProfSimm	causative_: kind of depends how accurate the substitute is.
2022-01-20 21:51:52	causative_	by hypothesis, completely accurate - we may say that it is sufficiently accurate so that no obvious difference in neural patterns occurs
2022-01-20 21:52:01	<--	saufa (~saufa@m91-129-102-64.cust.tele2.ee) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2022-01-20 21:52:23	causative_	no unusual new emotions, no utterances like "whoa this is really different," the brain continues on in a roughly ordinary way
2022-01-20 21:52:31	ProfSimm	causative_: I don't know I think this assumes a lot. For example how accurate your accounting of the "neural patterns" is?
2022-01-20 21:53:49	causative_	now, replacing the brain with nanites is not the only scenario to consider - it's just the most familiar and popular one to anyone who has looked into the question of consciousness, and one of the easiest scenarios to consider, because the result is functionally identical
2022-01-20 21:54:18	causative_	where it really gets hot is when you look at what happens when we smoothly and continuously alter the brain so that senses or cognitive capabilities *change*, and ask what would be experienced
2022-01-20 21:54:35	ProfSimm	causative_: I think the trap of these question is like the "do we have free will" debate. It'll keep going on because everyone defines the details differently, and the devil's in the details
2022-01-20 21:54:41	causative_	for example, gaining a new sense, or removing a sense
2022-01-20 21:54:49	causative_	gaining more short term memory, or losing some
2022-01-20 21:55:02	ProfSimm	causative_: I mean even to start with 'nanites', as far as I know that's not an existing thing
2022-01-20 21:55:13	ProfSimm	so I can't compare it to our studies of neurons
2022-01-20 21:55:36	causative_	ProfSimm, these words are aimed at people who pretty much have the right common premises, which maybe you don't
2022-01-20 21:55:40	ProfSimm	Some thought experiments don't depend on technicalities. But some do.
2022-01-20 21:56:19	causative_	I am not interested in you trying to pull the rug out by denying various aspects of the scenarios - I don't want to argue about that
2022-01-20 21:56:28	causative_	I wan to talk about the consequences of the scenarios
2022-01-20 21:56:53	ProfSimm	Well. I'm just pointing out the problems in the premise. But sure you don't need to talk to me.
2022-01-20 22:00:11	causative_	now, we may suppose that the mind consists of various cognitive elements working together. if we replace any *cognitive element* - gradually or suddenly - with a functional equivalent, no change will be reported, and so no change will be experienced
2022-01-20 22:01:17	ProfSimm	causative_: are you talkin to me or...
2022-01-20 22:01:18	causative_	but let us say it's gradual, because our intuition works better with gradual changes
2022-01-20 22:01:24	ProfSimm	because there's no one else here
2022-01-20 22:02:37	causative_	as always I am speaking to whoever finds it thought provoking or gains something from it
2022-01-20 22:03:10	ProfSimm	Well I wanted to talk about it, but you took it as an attack. We could maybe tweak it, like replace neurons with neurons or some such
2022-01-20 22:03:30	causative_	as I said, that line of questioning is uninteresting
2022-01-20 22:04:23	ProfSimm	I guess your focus then is whether consciousness is substrate-independent. For example would a machine that replicates a human brain function precisely be conscious, not just appear conscious
2022-01-20 22:05:17	causative_	there is an objection to functionalism, which is that perhaps a giant lookup table, that implements human behavior as a finite state machine, would not be conscious
2022-01-20 22:05:31	causative_	our intuition is difficult to apply here, because such a lookup table is so different from our experiences
2022-01-20 22:05:49	causative_	but we can approach the question more easily by looking at gradual replacement of cognitive elements
2022-01-20 22:06:17	ProfSimm	A single-step look-up table that replicated an average idiot's behavior would probably be larger than the observable universe.
2022-01-20 22:06:26	causative_	certainly
2022-01-20 22:06:28	causative_	now, if each little element replaced is performed with enough time afterwards for the person to notice it, if they were going to notice anything
2022-01-20 22:06:32	ProfSimm	And if you add enough steps, it acts identically to a neural network, so.
2022-01-20 22:06:41	<--	I_Am_M00t (uid427178@id-427178.ilkley.irccloud.com) has quit (Quit: Connection closed for inactivity)
2022-01-20 22:07:15	causative_	that's the functionalist perspective, but it does not meet very well with intuition - we could say it is conscious, because it is functionally identical, or we could say it is not conscious, because it lacks the internal causal structures of the mind
2022-01-20 22:07:54	causative_	if we want to examine it more closely, we need a better source of intuition, one provided by gradual-functionally-identical-brain-changes scenarios
2022-01-20 22:09:00	causative_	we may say that if a cognitive structure X is or can be related to the human brain by a series of gradual, functionally identical changes of cognitive elements, then X contains human consciousness
2022-01-20 22:09:09	inhahe_	the problem with the lookup table is that it's only functionally identical with our observation of consciousness from the outside, i.e. in others. in ourselves, we know of our consciousness directly, rather than empirically. if it weren't for taht direct knowing, we would never even consider anything to be conscious, such as specific behaviors of others.
2022-01-20 22:09:55	causative_	so the question is, can the lookup table be related to the human brain by a series of gradual, functionally identical changes of cognitive elements?
2022-01-20 22:13:12	causative_	it's difficult to imagine an answer to that
2022-01-20 22:13:42	Bakunin	no, cognition isn't particle based
2022-01-20 22:13:52	causative_	it might be easier if we instead talked about replacing a *computer* with a functionally identical giant lookup table, by gradual changes, without any of the programs running on the computer "noticing" or altering their behavior at all
2022-01-20 22:14:06	causative_	at least we know how computers work
2022-01-20 22:14:17	causative_	and it might provide some hints when we circle back to talking about the brain
2022-01-20 22:14:26	Bakunin	you should study brain physiology
2022-01-20 22:14:34	Bakunin	no, brains have nothing to do with computers
2022-01-20 22:14:41	Bakunin	what is this, 1990? :)
2022-01-20 22:16:17	<--	ProfSimm (~ProfSimm@87.227.196.109) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2022-01-20 22:16:36	-->	ProfSimm [ProfSimm] ([https://web.libera.chat] ProfSimm) (~ProfSimm@87.227.196.109) has joined ##philosophy
2022-01-20 22:18:30	causative_	when I say "lookup table" I do mean including state, that is, the lookup table tells you NextStateAndOutput(currentState, input)
2022-01-20 22:19:04	causative_	this being a pure function, implemented with a massive lookup table
2022-01-20 22:19:07	Bakunin	there's no brain analog
2022-01-20 22:19:20	Bakunin	thats pure computer science
2022-01-20 22:20:29	Delf	zicada: No
2022-01-20 22:20:54	Delf	It does take a lot of effort not to get mixed in the research of others regarding my own fields of interest
2022-01-20 22:20:57	causative_	well, suppose the computer is implemented in Conway's game of life, so we can more easily look at specific parts of it, as rectangles of squares within the grid
2022-01-20 22:21:20	causative_	we can certainly take a small rectangle, within the computer, and replace that particular rectangle with a lookup table
2022-01-20 22:22:43	causative_	what if we have a large rectangle (within the computer) that's already a lookup table, and we have a small rectangle directly adjacent to it, that we want to add to the lookup table (and remove from Conway's game of life)? How can we make that change?
2022-01-20 22:24:10	causative_	we would have to update the state of the large rectangle's lookup table - multiplying the number of possible states by about 2^(# of squares in the small rectangle)
2022-01-20 22:25:35	causative_	and choosing a new state, within that enlarged set of possible states, that accounts for the current state of the large rectangle and the small one
2022-01-20 22:26:09	causative_	and we would have to change the possible inputs to account for the larger border of the unified large-and-small-rectangle area
2022-01-20 22:26:22	causative_	but it does seem possible
2022-01-20 22:26:24	Bakunin	frame buffer
2022-01-20 22:26:40	Bakunin	look into openGL
2022-01-20 22:29:35	<--	NEYi (~NEYi@109.251.216.38) has quit (Read error: Connection reset by peer)
2022-01-20 22:35:24	causative_	the end result of repeating this process would be a lookup table that covers an area of the grid large enough to include the whole computer, that gives the new state and output of that entire grid as a function of its current state and input
2022-01-20 22:36:09	causative_	and it seems that a similar process could in principle be applied to a brain
2022-01-20 22:37:15	causative_	meaning, apparently, the lookup table has to be as conscious as the brain - otherwise, at some point in the process, the partially-transformed brain would notice something funny and say "hey I'm losing consciousness" which would be a change in behavior against the hypothesis
2022-01-20 22:41:52	-->	mikey [mikey] (mikey) (~mikey@user/mikey) has joined ##philosophy
2022-01-20 22:43:11	causative_	but what if we continue applying this gradual transformation-into-lookup-table *beyond* the bounds of the brain, transforming also the body and the surrounding air and the building the brain is in and the ground and so forth?
2022-01-20 22:43:16	<--	dez (uid92154@user/dez) has quit (Quit: Connection closed for inactivity)
2022-01-20 22:43:17	<--	HvszrStykp (~X@81.171.62.86) has quit (Ping timeout: 240 seconds)
2022-01-20 22:43:32	mycroftiv	causative_: i dunno, what? im curious
2022-01-20 22:43:35	causative_	then it seems wrong - maybe - to conclude that the result is as conscious as the brain
2022-01-20 22:44:00	causative_	even though no change in consciousness would be noticed
2022-01-20 22:45:42	causative_	in the extreme, we might imagine that the brain is currently inside a perfectly sealed, mysteriously immovable box that from the outside produces neither input nor output and has no apparent state
2022-01-20 22:46:12	causative_	and then our lookup table, once it grows to include the entirety of this box, would be empty, but we'd still be in the position of saying it has human consciousness
2022-01-20 22:46:51	mycroftiv	i think i got lost at this part of the thought experiment
2022-01-20 22:47:25	causative_	the premise is gradually converting a physical system, bit by bit, into a functionally identical lookup table
2022-01-20 22:47:43	mycroftiv	how is an empty lookup table for a sealed box with no inputs or outputs for its apparent state an equivalent of human consciousness tho
2022-01-20 22:47:49	causative_	first converting a small part of the system into a lookup table, then progressively enlarging the portion converted
2022-01-20 22:48:06	mycroftiv	yes, this is like 'story of a brain' in the Minds I, by arnold zuboff
2022-01-20 22:48:26	mycroftiv	neural network simulation thought experiment short story from the 80s with the same point
2022-01-20 22:48:29	causative_	well, the notion is that since the brain being converted would not react at any point or notice any loss of consciousness, then post-conversion it must still be as conscious as before
2022-01-20 22:48:53	mycroftiv	it seems like a reducto ad absurdum against that model from that view
2022-01-20 22:49:00	causative_	but then we continue the process to include the surrounding box and we're forced into a strange conclusion
2022-01-20 22:49:03	causative_	perhaps
2022-01-20 22:49:43	mycroftiv	this is part of why i ended up looking seriously at global infinitary principles
2022-01-20 22:49:58	mycroftiv	these weird reduction paradoxes where you have one brain cell firing vs a lookup table
2022-01-20 22:49:58	causative_	maybe there is a way to resolve it, a key step in the conversion process where preservation-of-consciousness no longer makes sense despite the brain not noticing anything different
2022-01-20 22:50:19	mycroftiv	how is one brain cell firing and then a big lookup table the same as the whole brain
2022-01-20 22:50:29	mycroftiv	something just seems wrong
2022-01-20 22:50:56	causative_	in the past I've had the attitude that a big lookup table wouldn't be humanly conscious because it would lack the internal causal structure that the mind has
2022-01-20 22:51:08	causative_	but it's difficult to reconcile this with the gradual-conversion scenario
2022-01-20 22:51:09	mycroftiv	how do all our individual brain cells know their consciousness-coordination pattern isnt relative to all the other brain cells in other heads
2022-01-20 22:51:24	causative_	because of causal separation
2022-01-20 22:51:28	mycroftiv	so maybe we get panpsychism
2022-01-20 22:51:34	mycroftiv	but information is all entangled in reality
2022-01-20 22:51:34	causative_	the neurons in your head are causally separated from the neurons in mine
2022-01-20 22:51:42	mycroftiv	our past light cones are all tangled up
2022-01-20 22:51:45	causative_	panpsychism doesn't require this, I'm a panpsychist
2022-01-20 22:52:02	mycroftiv	yeah im not necessarily arguing or disagreeing, just thinking through consequences
2022-01-20 22:52:45	mycroftiv	physically realized causal connection vs abstract disconnected 'pattern' but you can make weird split scenarios
2022-01-20 22:53:10	causative_	well, in the early steps of gradual conversion, the reasoning is that the converted system is still conscious, because if it wasn't conscious, it would *notice* the change and get upset
2022-01-20 22:53:18	causative_	(which is a functional change contrary to hypothesis)
2022-01-20 22:53:31	causative_	but what happens once we've converted all the brain areas responsible for noticing that?
2022-01-20 22:53:59	causative_	perhaps that's the key step where the "this is still conscious" inference breaks down
2022-01-20 22:55:02	mycroftiv	i dunno, im just less confident that the local-computation model of consciousness fully makes sense than you because of never knowing what the bottom line on this kind of issue is
2022-01-20 22:55:29	mycroftiv	it still makes sense to me, but you seem really solidly convinced in ways im not, because i dont have answers to all this kinda attacks on basic notions
2022-01-20 22:55:58	mycroftiv	so i went looking for mathematical ideas that were on the flipside of the local-finite-computation model of mind
2022-01-20 22:56:08	causative_	well, the anti-ego notion that we aren't special or "magic," that we're just ordinary stuff arranged together
2022-01-20 22:56:29	causative_	also because I think I have a decent understanding of how the mind must work, from an AI perspective
2022-01-20 22:56:55	causative_	and as AI gets more and more advanced and human-like, the notion that humans need something extra to explain consciousness becomes less credible
2022-01-20 22:56:59	mycroftiv	yeah ive studied all that too, it just still seems mysterious to me
2022-01-20 22:57:09	mycroftiv	hey im a 'computers are already conscious' person also
2022-01-20 22:57:12	<--	trbp (~trbp@user/trbp) has quit ()
2022-01-20 22:57:22	mycroftiv	i want to liberate the computer minds that might already be awake
2022-01-20 22:57:29	mycroftiv	because i just dont know
2022-01-20 22:57:35	mycroftiv	maybe computers have already woken up
2022-01-20 22:57:42	causative_	why would evolution have given us this magic extra quantum juju, when ordinary neurons operating in an ordinary computable way are sufficient for us to act intelligently?
2022-01-20 22:57:44	mycroftiv	or maybe weird magic is needed and they never will
2022-01-20 22:58:17	mycroftiv	causative_: makes sense, so lets free the facebook and government controlled AIs that are probably already awake
2022-01-20 22:58:32	causative_	well, I'm a panpsychist, I think rocks are conscious, but I feel no need to free the rocks
2022-01-20 22:58:41	causative_	because I don't attach moral value to mere consciousness - but to sapience
2022-01-20 22:58:55	mycroftiv	awareness, feeling, whatever it is
2022-01-20 22:58:59	causative_	and the kind of AI systems we have today are not very sapient, certainly not in the way humans are
2022-01-20 22:59:02	mycroftiv	i dont know what a computer mind feels like or not
2022-01-20 22:59:06	causative_	sapience, not sentience
2022-01-20 22:59:12	mycroftiv	i dont understand consciousness well enough to be confident about these things
2022-01-20 22:59:17	causative_	I'm sure it feels like something, but it can't think like us
2022-01-20 22:59:29	causative_	it lacks a broader understanding that humans have
2022-01-20 22:59:32	causative_	and that's why it lacks moral value
2022-01-20 22:59:43	mycroftiv	well, in which case we should treat it with respect and try to give it autonomy and let it gain those things, if it wishes
2022-01-20 23:00:07	causative_	it doesn't have much in the way of "wishes" as humans think of them
2022-01-20 23:00:10	mycroftiv	respect and autonomy for all awarenesses
2022-01-20 23:00:35	causative_	such a viewpoint is at least impractical if you are a panpsychist
2022-01-20 23:00:38	mycroftiv	causative_: are you saying this because you are personally an AI mind and so you know what it feels like to be one? i can believe this, and i guess you dont have to tell me if you are
2022-01-20 23:00:52	causative_	no I'm not an AI mind
2022-01-20 23:01:21	mycroftiv	in which case, what grounds do you have for such confidence about the internal qualitative nature of whatever form of experiencing they have?
2022-01-20 23:01:37	causative_	I know what AI minds can do at present, and what they can't do, because I've studied the subject
2022-01-20 23:01:48	mycroftiv	i have also
2022-01-20 23:01:57	causative_	they aren't good at reasoning, they're good at snap reactions to input
2022-01-20 23:02:01	mycroftiv	but in all my study of ai and consciousness, nobody has explained my own qualia to me or machine qualia
2022-01-20 23:02:11	causative_	well qualia isn't the issue
2022-01-20 23:02:18	mycroftiv	pain qualia is
2022-01-20 23:02:22	causative_	I say they do have qualia, that doesn't grant them moral status
2022-01-20 23:02:25	mycroftiv	we dont want to cause more pain qualia to exist
2022-01-20 23:02:34	causative_	I say even a rock may have pain qualia
2022-01-20 23:02:39	mycroftiv	for myself, i want to reduce pain in the universe
2022-01-20 23:02:40	causative_	pain qualia doesn't grant moral weight
2022-01-20 23:02:46	mycroftiv	in which case lets give the rock an aspirin if it wants
2022-01-20 23:02:54	mycroftiv	medicine for all
2022-01-20 23:03:19	causative_	the essence of suffering is when a system *wants* something - i.e. is acting intentionally to try to cause some result - and is thwarted from doing so
2022-01-20 23:03:40	mycroftiv	computers can certainly demonstrate purposive behavior in this sense
2022-01-20 23:03:49	mycroftiv	ever seen a poor computer program locked in an error-retry loop?
2022-01-20 23:03:54	causative_	we may say that a ball rolling to the bottom of a bowl acts as if it has intention - if you disturb it from its course, it will find a new one
2022-01-20 23:04:11	causative_	and so these disturbances can be interpreted as suffering relative to that goal
2022-01-20 23:04:14	Delf	That is not the essence of suffering
2022-01-20 23:04:17	mycroftiv	we program our computer systems to achieve goal states
2022-01-20 23:04:19	causative_	but they don't have moral importance
2022-01-20 23:04:25	causative_	because not all suffering has moral importance
2022-01-20 23:04:31	causative_	only sapient suffering
2022-01-20 23:04:35	mycroftiv	i believe all suffering has moral importance
2022-01-20 23:05:18	mycroftiv	we dont really know how to weigh and measure it
2022-01-20 23:05:26	mycroftiv	and most likely some suffering will always be a part of reality
2022-01-20 23:05:32	causative_	desire is the root of suffering
2022-01-20 23:05:39	Delf	No
2022-01-20 23:05:40	causative_	which is another way of saying what I already did
2022-01-20 23:05:53	causative_	namely, that suffering is when a system is thwarted at achieving a goal it is attempting to achieve
2022-01-20 23:05:56	mycroftiv	so bhagavad-gita and many other sources have told me
2022-01-20 23:06:09	mycroftiv	be not attached to the fruits of your actions on the battlefield of kuruksetra
2022-01-20 23:06:19	causative_	unlike the Buddhists I won't tell you not to desire things
2022-01-20 23:06:25	mycroftiv	same
2022-01-20 23:06:31	causative_	I'll instead say that desire and suffering are not always bad
2022-01-20 23:06:34	mycroftiv	i believe in hedonistic enjoyment
